==English==
===Etymology===
From Greek prefix ''[[hetero-]]'' "different" + [[clitic]]

===Adjective===
'''heteroclitic'''

# {{Grammar}} In linguistics (particularly [[Proto-Indo-European]] studies), a stem which alternates between more than one form when declined for grammatical [[case]]. Examples of heteroclitic noun stems in Proto-Indo-European include '''*wodr-''' "water" ([[nominoaccusative]] '''*wódr'''; [[genitive]] '''*wednós'''; [[locative]] *wedén) and '''*yêk<sup>w</sup>r-''' "liver" ([[nominoaccusative]] '''*yêk<sup>w</sup>r''', genitive '''*yek<sup>w</sup>nós'''). In Proto-Indo-European, heteroclitic stems tend to be noun stems with grammatically [[inanimate]] gender.